Intern Narratives - Part 1

Leisha Murthy
Tehsin Amlani
Matthew Krill

2 days ago   14 min read

Key Insights

  • Twelve crypto-native interns from elite schools across the country cover their most exciting upcoming narratives for 2024. The first of this two-part report covers AI, gaming, and stablecoin adoption.
  • AI x Crypto (Data Layer): The growing demand for high-quality AI training data has led to the emergence of crypto networks that incentivize data generation, although the field is still in its infancy.
  • Decentralized Gaming: Onchain gaming is regaining momentum with a significant increase in TVL, but the sector faces skepticism due to past failures in incentive models. The success of new models hinges on balancing rewards and user engagement.
  • Stablecoin Adoption: Latin America's adoption of stablecoins, especially USDT, is driven by high inflation and unstable local currencies, with Argentina and Venezuela leading the charge as citizens seek to protect their savings against hyperinflation.

Messari hired twelve intern analysts from elite schools over the summer. They worked with different research teams Protocol Services, Diligence, and Enterprise. While their time with Messari didn't "retire them from a 100x trade", they did (hopefully) gain a broad understanding of our research process.

For their time with the Enterprise team, they were asked to cover six narratives in teams of two in the style of our own Narrative Games. These are the narratives they believe are most compelling for the next 3-6 months based on the potential for hype, financial gain, and technology adoption. The framework for comparing different narratives is based on the following criteria:

  • Supply Overhang: A supply overhang affects a token's supply-demand balance, influencing price movements and investor sentiment. A large supply overhang can reduce investor enthusiasm and confidence, making even strong narratives lose momentum.
  • Impact: Impact highlights a narrative's transformative potential. A narrative with significant impact means the project can solve real problems, drive adoption, or offer substantial benefits over existing solutions. Impactful narratives also help distinguish a project from competitors, positioning it as a leader in innovation and value creation.
  • Probability: First, market participants should assess the likelihood of a protocol or sector delivering on its promises. If a team cannot turn its story into reality, the narrative is useless. Second, probability analysis can gauge the likelihood of other market participants buying into a narrative. Even if a narrative identifies a technological shift, it doesnt guarantee market attention. This is like a tree falling in a forest with no one to hear it did it happen?
  • Consensus: A consensus narrative can also limit upside potential. When a narrative is widely accepted, much of the growth may already be priced in, reducing the opportunity for substantial gains. The best trades are often those with high conviction but without market consensus.

This is Part 1 of a two-part report where the Messari Summer Interns of 2024 cover their narratives.

Narrative Games: AI x Crypto - Data Solution

Authors: Leisha Murthy, Tehsin Amlani

There is an increasing scarcity of data available to further train and refine AI models, which is driving demand for high-quality training data. Similar to humans, AI models require substantial data for effective analysis and learning.

Historically, model performance has improved by training larger and more complex models with increasing amounts of data. However, this practice has led to a phenomenon known as the data wall, where the quantity and quality of available data are becoming insufficient for further training.

Frontier AI models have utilized nearly all accessible data on the internet, creating a bottleneck for researchers who seek to enhance model performance but are constrained by the lack of data.

Crypto networks are particularly adept at incentivizing specific behaviors and bootstrapping marketplaces, making them well-positioned to address this market need by encouraging users to generate or contribute data directly to models or data marketplaces.

Framework Evaluation

Data solutions in the AI x Crypto space are in their infancy. While some have liquid tokens (i.e., TAO, MASA), most other protocols have yet to launch a token. We then expect there to be a fair amount of supply overhang, given the token generation events have yet to occur for protocols in this category.

The impact of crypto data solutions is high but still invites skepticism due to their early stage. However, the below protocols leverage web2's experiences with AI, targeting specific blind spots like data transparency and control that web2 has struggled to address.

Synthetic data, widely used in Web2, presents challenges due to the expensive and lengthy process of dataset creation and validation. DRIA, a synthetic data generation tool, and Vana, a platform for creating specific data pools, generate up-to-date data from publicly available sources like Reddit and Twitter.

Additionally, users cannot currently verify the source of data used to train AI models. Grass plans to solve this issue with a layer 2 data rollup that embeds metadata in datasets and creates zero-knowledge proofs for on-chain settlement on Solana. The lack of real-time data is another challenge being tackled by DePIN data collectors like Hivemapper and DIMO. Lastly, Masa solves the problem of outdated and insufficient AI training data by providing real-time, specialized datasets through its Bittensor Subnet.

While protocols like Grass and Bittensor have demonstrated proof of concept, newer projects like Delphia and DIMO are still working to prove their viability.

Success in this space hinges on the probability of successfully building compelling user incentive data marketplaces and executing on AI dataset generation to address web2 AI industry challenges. Despite a consensus on the need for these solutions, concerns about the quality of execution remain due to the industry's early stage.

This evaluation will focus on the solutions to address AI data scarcity, including general and specific datasets, and incentivized data marketplaces.

Tailwinds

New Economic Drivers

The success of the marketplace model in crypto has led to the emergence of data marketplaces (Grass), creating a new economy where users earn passive income for contributing data that is used for AI training.

New Dataset Retrieval and Sorting Methods

Decentralized networks targeting specialized datasets are exploring untapped Web2 markets. The DePIN data collection boom is set to deliver new, specific data for AI training (Hivemapper, Vana), thereby opening up novel opportunities for AI development.

The protocols use two methods to address data scarcity: scraping public websites for mass data collection (Grass) and utilizing synthetic data sets.

Unlike normal datasets, which are collected from actual sources, synthetic datasets are algorithmically generated to mimic similar patterns and structures of public data without privacy or ethical concerns. The overarching goal is to use synthetic datasets for targeted AI training, creating more specific models for niche use cases.

Headwinds

Investment Valuation

Unit economics for decentralized data marketplaces remain unclear, complicating the justification of their value and long-term sustainability. For example, a sophisticated, mature company like Facebook averaged just $11.95 in revenue per user in Q224. In contrast, decentralized protocols often lack defined monetization strategies and clear incentives for participation.

Unknown Market Fit

Many decentralized protocols are in their early stages or proof-of-concept phases, often lacking transparency in their training processes and proven market fit. The absence of historical success hinders their ability to gain trust and adoption from potential market participants.

Economic Incentives

Data marketplaces have adopted the user incentive approach, which has historically been effective in bootstrapping protocol adoption. However, as these incentives diminish over time, sustained real demand becomes crucial for ensuring long-term success and competing with traditional technology companies.

Decentralized Gaming

Authors: Matthew Krill, Matt Zhang

Decentralized gaming leverages blockchain technology to create an open, player-driven game economy. Web2 gaming business models designate ownership of games and in-game items to the publishers and centralized entities. Publishers such as Ubisoft and Apple are increasingly moving towards subscription-based services, requiring continual payments from consumers in order to access their platforms and games.

Onchain gaming makes in-game assets composable and programmable, granting players verifiable ownership of the game. By facilitating direct onchain transactions, onchain gaming enables players and developers to monetize together, fostering a more egalitarian ecosystem.

Blockchain-based gaming remains a nascent sector that, despite experiencing a significant decline in 2021, has gradually begun to regain its momentum. Onchain gaming Total Value Locked (TVL) is up over 65% YoY, rising from $2.2 million to just under $4 million. The increase in gaming TVL can be directly attributed to the notable growth in funding and deal volume, which saw investments totaling $1.1 billion in Q2 2024. During this period, a16z announced a $600 million gaming fund, Bitcraft Ventures began raising their third GameFi fund totaling $275 million, Arbitrum DAO approved a $215 million gaming ecosystem fund, and NPC Labs, founded by ex-Coinbase staff, raised $21 million to build gaming infrastructure on Base.

Framework Evaluation

As of July 2024, there are over 994 quality, playable Web3 games across 70 blockchains. These games exhibit a wide range of integrations with blockchain technology, from minimal to fully onchain implementations. Fully onchain games, which represent the extreme end of this spectrum, are often viewed as overengineered for many use cases. Most onchain games fall somewhere between minimal and partial integration, the primary benefit being tokenized asset ownership. GameFi continues to rise in popularity with 7 million unique active addresses, introducing new options like cross-ecosystem integration and decentralized governance for game improvements and updates.

Supply overhangs are introduced in decentralized gaming through incentive imbalances. When rewards are too high, inflation soars, and when rewards are few, users are disincentivized from participating. As a result, finding the perfect balance has been a struggle for many past and current game developers.

The low probability of success for onchain gaming stems from the inherent mistrust of blockchain gaming incentives. Unfortunately, for many crypto investors, the Web3 game economy is dominated by speculators and players focused solely on extracting financial value. The Play-to-Earn (P2E) model and similar systems have historically lacked engagement and a stable player base. However, many argue that gaming retains significant potential to replace traditional triple-A studios, using decentralized governance and asset ownership as potential incentives to help onboard users and address issues present in the Web2 gaming industry. Alternative models that encourage developer creativity have emerged, yet have also encountered roadblocks. The skill-to-earn system is becoming increasingly popular, which rewards player experience and skill instead of time. However, the advent of bots introduces a cat-and-mouse dilemma of bot detection that can be detrimental to overall gameplay and user experience.

Tailwinds

A market niche within the decentralized gaming ecosystem known as "GameFi" is a portmanteau of "game and finance. GameFi offers various models like Play-to-Earn (P2E), Play-and-Earn, Play-to-Own, Stake-to-Earn, yield farming, and game mining, allowing players to monetize their time and skills. Unlike traditional games, where value remains confined within the game environment that results in net-zero transactions, GameFi creates an interconnected ecosystem of marketplaces that facilitate value-generating transactions for players and developers. For this trend to continue, games must be enjoyable and well-monetized to retain players who seek both fun and financial rewards.

The introduction of account abstraction has helped lower the barriers of entry for traditional users by hiding the technical processes of blockchainsuch as managing addresses and transactionsmaking the user experience more seamless and intuitive. For example, Immutable Passport transforms crypto wallets into customizable smart contract wallets, providing a unified and secure login experience across multiple games and platforms. This solution has seen rapid adoption, with user signups growing 150% from 400,000 in April to over 1 million in May 2024.

Headwinds

Crypto itself is already challenging for adoption, requiring the use of wallets and private keys that many Web2 users are traditionally unaccustomed to. Compared to Web2 gaming, where purchases and MFA are often the only barriers to gameplay, blockchains inherent complexity can be detrimental to consumer adoption. In addition, frequent scandals and adverse media can deter otherwise eager adopters from engaging with new releases.

Most Web2 games are pay-to-play, meaning users are charged to gain access to and enjoy games created by a developer. In essence, you pay money to enjoy hours (hopefully) of fun. These roles are reversed in Web3 gaming, allowing users to profit - yet, this can also remove the fun from the equation. For developers, mechanisms that enable the acquisition of liquid assets become the central focus of their games, which often leads to low game quality that deters both Web2 and Web3 gamers. For those who participate, gaming can become a second job as the entire player base is focused on earning tokens. While this may be beneficial for users in countries where the local currency is weak, this is an unattractive proposition for most.

Stablecoin Adoption in Latin America

Authors: Elliot Sternberg, Juan Cruz Assad

Stablecoins represent a ~$160 billion asset class within the crypto market, characterized by their price being pegged to an external asset, most commonly the US Dollar. This alternative to the traditional fiat-backed financial system has gained significant traction in emerging markets, particularly in Latin America. The region has historically suffered from a lack of access to the banking system and the devaluation of local currencies. Various country-specific themes can largely explain the adoption of stablecoins in the region.

Framework Evaluation

Driven by high inflation rates and rising cross-border payment fees, Latin America has resorted to stablecoin adoption like a life vest amongst a sinking boat. Despite Bitcoins value proposition as a hedge against inflation, stablecoins are preferred by most crypto adopters of the region. According to a report released by Kaiko, more than 40% of all trades taking place in Latin America involve USDT.

With a yearly inflation rate of over 200% in 2023, Argentina has spearheaded USDT adoption as a hedge against hyperinflation. As the Argentinian peso continuously loses value, the purchase of cryptocurrencies increases, spiking significantly in mid-April when Argentina's inflation rate surpassed 100% for the first time in thirty years. Lemon Cash, an Argentina-based crypto exchange with 2M+ users, reported that the most deposited tokens are USDT, USDC, and BTC. On the platform, 34.2% of the deposits are USDT through the BEP20 network, and 29.0% are USDT through TRC20. Argentineans are turning to USDT to fight inflation and Argentinas regulation against US Dollar purchases. Looking forward, the nations president, far-right libertarian Javier Milei, has expressed interest in dollarizing the Argentinean economy. However, its unclear whether stablecoins will be a part of this initiative.

Like Argentina, Venezuela has suffered its fair share of economic problems and record-level hyperinflation. Venezuelans have also resorted to stables as they provide an alternative method of transacting amidst an authoritarian regime. Peer-to-peer companies such as El Dorado have emerged for buying and selling USDT TRC20 and USDC on Polygon, as well as Coco Pago to send remittances into the country using USDT on Solana. The Circle and Airtm partnership enabled the bypassing of financial controls imposed by Maduros regime to allow USDC funds to be sent to hospitals and those with medical needs. As the lack of trust continues to increase based on recent developments in the political landscape, stablecoins will remain attractive.

In addition to hedging against hyperinflation, lower fees for remittance payments have been another adoption incentive for stablecoins. Mexico is currently the world's second-largest recipient of remittances, representing ~3.7% of its GDP. A majority of remittances have historically gone to the poorest areas in Mexico, increasing financial freedom for the unbanked. Bitsos CEO has reported that over $3.3 billion in crypto remittances were sent from the U.S. to Mexico in 2022 through the platform. With the increased instability throughout the country coupled with the support of current president Andrs Manuel Lpez Obrador, this use case has the potential to continue gaining adoption.

Tailwinds

Open Market Adoption

Multiple private companies have driven crypto adoption throughout the region, taking the initiative despite a loose regulatory framework. In May 2024, Banco Galicia, the largest Argentinian private bank, launched its crypto trading offering for the region. As a result of this traction, governments are taking action to provide clarity for early adopters. For example, in March 2024, Argentina made registration for crypto exchanges mandatory. If the adoption of stablecoins continues to grow in the open market, the government and regulation will follow.

Increased LaTam-Focused Initiatives

In addition to the development of global stablecoins with companies like Circle and Tether, theres been an increase in the development of region-native solutions where settlement occurs in the local currency of a given country. Through innovative products such as Sling Money that enable seamless conversion into any currency and the integration of Taproot Assets to bring stablecoins to the Lightning Network, these ideas could bring a new wave of opportunities.

Headwinds

Illicit Transactions

Stablecoins could be used to evade sanctions, like Venezuelas state owned oil and gas company PDVSAs recent ramp-up in USDT usage to avoid funds being frozen by the U.S. government. To combat this, Tether has previously partnered with the US Government, as seen in December 2023 when they froze 161 wallets in compliance with US sanctions.

Regulatory Arbitrage

Currently, USDT usage in Argentina is predominantly unregulated. Even though CEX usage in Argentina is relatively high, most of the population on-ramps through the use of cuevas. Argentinas cepo law limits citizens to only purchase USD 200 per month. Cuevas are hidden stores throughout the city that allow consumers to buy USD with cash. These cuevas use USDT to bypass the law and purchase more than USD 200 per month. However, none of these transactions are regulated.
